http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Business_cycle\" title=\"Business cycle\">economic fluctuations<\/a> and ... penetrating analysis of the interdependence of economic, social and institutional phenomena\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Hayek was a major social theorist and political philosopher of the twentieth century,<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> and his account of how <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Price_signal\" title=\"Price signal\">changing prices communicate information<\/a> which enables individuals to co-ordinate their plans is widely regarded as an important achievement in economics.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Hayek served in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/World_War_I\" title=\"World War I\">World War I<\/a> and said that his experience in the war and his desire to help avoid the mistakes that had led to the war led him to his career. Hayek lived in Austria, Great Britain, the United States and Germany, and became a British subject in 1938. He spent most of his academic life at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/London_School_of_Economics\" title=\"London School of Economics\">London School of Economics<\/a> (LSE), the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Chicago\" title=\"University of Chicago\">University of Chicago<\/a>, and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Freiburg\" title=\"University of Freiburg\">University of Freiburg<\/a>.<\/p><p>In 1984, he was appointed a member of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Order_of_the_Companions_of_Honour\" title=\"Order of the Companions of Honour\">Order of the Companions of Honour<\/a> by <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Elizabeth_II\" title=\"Elizabeth II\">Queen Elizabeth II<\/a> on the advice of Prime Minister <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Margaret_Thatcher\" title=\"Margaret Thatcher\">Margaret Thatcher<\/a> for his \"services to the study of economics\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Ebenstein_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-Ebenstein-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was the first recipient of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hanns_Martin_Schleyer_Prize\" title=\"Hanns Martin Schleyer Prize\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Hanns Martin Schleyer Prize<\/a> in 1984.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He also received the US <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Presidential_Medal_of_Freedom\" title=\"Presidential Medal of Freedom\">Presidential Medal of Freedom<\/a> in 1991 from President <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_H._W._Bush\" title=\"George H. W. Bush\">George H. W. Bush<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-7\"><span>[<\/span>7<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> In 2011, his article \"<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_Use_of_Knowledge_in_Society\" title=\"The Use of Knowledge in Society\">The Use of Knowledge in Society<\/a>\" was selected as one of the top 20 articles published in <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_American_Economic_Review\" title=\"The American Economic Review\">The American Economic Review<\/a><\/i> during its first 100 years.<sup id=\"cite_ref-top_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Friedrich_Hayek#cite_note-top-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Friedrich Hayek","place_of_birth":"Vienna, Austria-Hungary","place_of_death":"Freiburg, Germany","text":"Friedrich Hayek , Economics, 1974","year":1974.0}